The course provides an overview of the historical development of design, starting with the Arts and Crafts movement at the end of the 19th century. Design styles in this context are inseparable from the general beliefs and aesthetic values of the given era. The aim of the course is to highlight the different historical schools that influence our artificial environment to this day (Bauhaus, De Stijl, Art Nouveau, Streamline, etc.). Through historical changes in man's artificial environment, the course participant learns to see the connections between craft, design and technology.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The purpose of the course is to provide a historical overview of the changes in design styles throughout the 20th century and to examine the role of technology and craft in design.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  After passing the course student
Upon successful completion of the subject, the students should
- Can distinguish between different design styles and schools
- Can relate the design style to the broader cultural background system of the given era
- Understands the connections between historical craft technology and modern mass production.
- Understands the role of the industrial revolution in changing design and the general artificial environment.
